/*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*\
  optim05_reactor_npv  --  CONSTRAINED ECONOMIC optimisation: size & operate an
                           esterification CSTR plant for MAXIMUM NPV.

  Same esterification plant as the economics01 flagship --

      feed --> reactor (CSTR) --> heater --> separator (flash)
                                                 |-> vapProd (ethyl-acetate-rich
                                                 |            overhead, the prime
                                                 |            product @ 1.55 EUR/kg)
                                                 |-> liqProd (water/acid-rich
                                                              bottoms, low-value
                                                              byproduct @ 0.30 EUR/kg)

  -- but instead of a FIXED design we ask the engine the design question:

      maximise   economics.NPV
      varying    V_R     (reactor volume,        m^3)
                 T_feed  (feed/reactor T,        K)
      subject to reactor.V_R    <=  V_max   (a physical SIZE cap)
                 economics.FCI  <=  FCI_max (a CAPITAL-BUDGET cap)

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  THE ECONOMIC TRADE-OFF (why this is a genuine optimum, not a corner)
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  The heater runs at a FIXED partial duty, so the downstream flash SPLITS the
  reactor effluent into a light, ethyl-acetate-rich VAPOUR overhead (sold high)
  and a heavy, water/acid-rich LIQUID bottoms (sold cheap).  Esterification
  conserves total mass; what conversion buys you is the RESHUFFLING of that mass
  toward the valuable overhead.  Both knobs raise conversion -- and the CSTR is
  ISOTHERMAL at the feed temperature (CSTR.cpp: T = feed.T), so:

    * V_R  (reactor volume) -- bigger V_R raises the residence time tau = V_R/Q,
      so conversion X = k.tau/(1 + k.tau) climbs, more acetic acid + ethanol turn
      into ethyl acetate, and the priced overhead grows and enriches
      (REVENUE up).  But a bigger vessel costs more steel: the StirredTank
      sizing -> Guthrie costing drives FCI (CAPEX) UP.  Revenue rises with
      DIMINISHING returns as X saturates toward 1, while CAPEX keeps climbing --
      so an NPV maximum exists.

    * T_feed (feed/reactor temperature) -- higher T raises the Arrhenius rate
      constant k = A.exp(-Ea/RT), so X climbs too.  T_feed is the cheap
      conversion ACCELERATOR; its bounds are kept inside the window where the
      flash splits cleanly (below the temperature that boils the bottoms dry).

  We deliberately set the size cap TIGHTER than where the NPV-greedy design
  would otherwise stop, so at the optimum the reactor-size constraint BINDS.

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  HOW TO READ THE SHADOW PRICES (the whole point of the tutorial)
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  The SQP prints, at the certified optimum, a Lagrange multiplier (lambda) for
  each inequality.  A constraint with lambda > 0 is ACTIVE (binding) and its
  multiplier is the SHADOW PRICE -- the marginal NPV you would gain by relaxing
  that cap by one unit:

    * reactor.V_R cap   ACTIVE  ->  lambda = d(NPV)/d(V_max)   [EUR of NPV per
                                    extra m^3 of reactor head-room].
    * economics.FCI cap         ->  lambda = d(NPV)/d(FCI_max) [EUR of NPV per
                                    extra EUR of capital you may spend].

  A constraint with lambda ~ 0 is SLACK (not binding) -- relaxing it buys
  nothing.  Here the FCI cap is deliberately generous: it stays SLACK so the
  student sees BOTH an active and an inactive constraint side by side.  The
  trace marks the active set and the KKT certificate proves the point is a true
  constrained optimum (||grad L|| ~ 0, complementarity ~ 0).

  The two design variables are case-level $references so the SQP can drive them
  through `variables.<name>` and the trace shows their canonical-SI values.
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

variables
{
    V_R        4.0;          // manipulated: reactor volume   [m^3], inside [0.3, 520]
    T_feed     350.0 K;      // manipulated: feed / reactor temperature  [K]
}

streams
{
    feed
    {
        F            500.0 kmol/h;
        T            $T_feed;            // <-- design variable (sets reactor T)
        P            1.01325 bar;
        molarComposition  { ethanol 0.5;  aceticAcid 0.5;  ethylAcetate 0.0;  water 0.0; }
    }
}

units
(
    {
        name        reactor;
        type        cstr;
        in          feed;
        outputs     ( reactorOut );

        operation   { V_R $V_R; }        // <-- design variable [m^3]
        reaction    esterification_etac;
    }

    {
        name        heater;
        type        heater;
        in          reactorOut;
        outputs     ( hotStream );

        operation   { Q  2.0e5 W; }      // fixed partial duty -- splits the flash
    }

    {
        name        separator;
        type        isothermalFlash;
        in          hotStream;
        outputs     ( liqProd  vapProd );

        operation   { P 1.0 bar; }
    }
);
